Sub-Saharan Africa Stocks: Equity, Skye, Standard Chartered, UTB

-- B y   M o s e s   M o z a r t   D z a w u   a n d   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a
-- 
2011-04-29T14:38:13Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-28/sub-saharan-africa-stocks-kenya-airways-kenya-commercial-bank.html
The  Ghana  Stock Exchange Composite
Index climbed for a fifth day, advancing 0.2 percent to 1,101 by
the 3 p.m. close in Accra.  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index rose for a fourth day,
strengthening 0.1 percent to 2,063.01 at the 1.30 p.m. close in
 Port Louis .  Kenya ’s All-Share Index advanced 0.6 percent to
75.34 by 3 p.m. in Nairobi.  Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  increased 0.2 percent
to 874.97 by 3:36 p.m. in Windhoek.  The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index dropped 0.2
percent to 25,241.46 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, the
commercial capital, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Equity Bank Ltd. (EQBNK)  , Kenya’s biggest lender by
market value, advanced after announcing first-quarter profit
surged 87 percent to 2.33 billion shillings ($27.9 million).  The shares climbed 5 cents, or 1.9 percent, to 27
shillings.  Skye Bank Plc (SKYEBANK)  , a Nigerian lender, fell to its
lowest in almost 11 weeks after being downgraded to “neutral”
from “outperform” at CSL Stockbrokers Ltd.  The stock lost 41 kobo, or 4.7 percent, to 8.29 naira by
the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos. That’s the lowest since Feb. 14
and brings its decline this year to 5.8 percent.  Standard Chartered  Bank Ghana Ltd. (SCB GN) fell the most
in more than nine months after saying first-quarter profit
declined 37 percent to 14 million cedis ($9.3 million).  The stock dropped 3.25 cedis, or 5.4 percent, to 56.75
cedis, the most since July 8, 2010.  UT Bank Ltd. (UTB)  , a lender in Ghana, rose to the
highest in nearly four weeks as its first-quarter profit soared
more than sevenfold to 1.1 million cedis.  The stock gained 2 pesewas, or 7.4 percent, to 29 pesewas,
the highest since April 4.  To contact the reporters on this story:
